📄 Shell Script Example (with comments)
File name: system_info.sh
#!/bin/bash # ----------------------------------------- 
# Script Name : system_info.sh 
# Purpose : Display basic system details
 # Author : Vishal # Date : 2026-02-09 # ----------------------------------------- 
# Print a welcome message echo "===== System Information Script =====" # Display current user echo "User: $(whoami)"
 # Display hostname echo "Hostname: $(hostname)"
 # Display current date and time echo "Date & Time: $(date)" 
# Display system uptime echo "Uptime:" uptime # Display disk usage echo "Disk Usage:" df -h
 # Display memory usage echo "Memory Usage:" free -h 
# End of script echo "===== Script Finished Successfully ====="
📝 Notes / Explanation (Important for Learning)
1️⃣ Shebang
#!/bin/bash

Tells Linux which shell to use


Always keep this on the first line


/bin/bash = Bash shell path



2️⃣ Comments
# This is a comment

Lines starting with # are ignored by the shell


Used for documentation (very important in DevOps)



3️⃣ echo
echo "Hello"

Prints output to the terminal


Used for messages and logs



4️⃣ Command Substitution
$(command)

Example:
echo "User: $(whoami)"

Runs a command and inserts its output


Old style: `whoami` (not recommended)



5️⃣ Common Linux Commands Used
Command
Purpose
whoami
Shows current user
hostname
System name
date
Current date & time
uptime
How long system is running
df -h
Disk usage (human readable)
free -h
Memory usage


▶️ How to Run This Script
Step 1: Create file
nano system_info.sh

Step 2: Give execute permission
chmod +x system_info.sh

Step 3: Run it
./system_info.sh


🔑 Key Shell Script Rules
Script must be executable


Commands run top to bottom


Spaces matter (especially in conditions)


Use comments to explain logic



